The concept of matching theory developed by economist Alvin Roth is to determine the final combination based on the preferences of the parties involved.
Colleagues Will Jones and Alex Taitelboim have explored how to apply this concept to refugees, asking refugees to list their desired destinations in order of preference and, at the same time, asking host countries to prioritize refugees based on job skills, language, and other conditions of the desired refugee type, and then matching the two.
Now, of course, when considering the conditions of the acceptance framework, elements such as diversity and vulnerability should be taken into account, but this can also be considered as a method to increase the matching rate.
An example of the successful application of the concept of matching is seen in university admission quotas for students and kidney donors with patients, as well as algorithms used in dating websites.
