Therefore, by conducting market matching, it is possible to align the preferences of both parties and hear the needs and requests from both the residents of the host community and the refugees.
And the fourth idea is humanitarian visas.
Most of the tragedies and chaos happening in Europe are completely avoidable.
The fundamental contradiction in Europe's refugee regulations is causing this. What this means is that in order to seek asylum in Europe, one must arrive without prior preparation on the infamous dangerous journey. But why is such a journey necessary?
In this day and age when budget airlines and consular services are well-established, such journeys should not be necessary at all, yet last year, over 3,000 people died due to this. This occurred at the borders of Europe and within European countries.
Simply put, the solution to avoidable refugee tragedies in Europe lies in allowing refugees to travel to Europe normally and become asylum seekers. The method to achieve this is through something called humanitarian visas, which can be obtained at embassies or consulates in neighboring countries. Then, refugees can simply pay for their own travel expenses and travel to Europe by ferry or plane.
It costs 1,000 euros to cross from Turkey to the islands of Greece using smugglers.
A budget airline ticket from Bodrum to Frankfurt costs 200 euros.
There are significant benefits to opening up these options for refugees.
Many lives will be saved, and the refugee smuggling industry itself will be affected, leading to a decrease in chaos at the forefront of Europe, such as the islands of Greece.
What is obstructing such means is not rational measures, but policies.
This idea has actually been implemented.
Brazil took the lead in adopting this approach, with over 2,000 Syrians obtaining humanitarian visas to enter Brazil and gaining refugee status upon arrival.
All Syrians who have utilized this system have obtained refugee status and received official refugee recognition.
There are historical precedents as well.
Between 1922 and 1942, using Nansen passports as international identification documents, 450,000 Assyrians, Turks, and Chechens moved within Europe and applied for refugee status in other European countries.
The Nansen International Office for Refugees has been awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, recognizing the effectiveness of this pragmatic strategy.
